metadata.name: Crash Euphoria #133
metadata.description:
My first foray into shaders and GLSL: This piece experiments with layering many textures guided by an underlying pattern. Each pixel value dictates which pattern is displayed. There are varying levels of imperfections in each pattern, some choose a single color, some use a color guide pattern, some individual strokes decide on another color altogether. These layers are compiled in a shader and warped.

Press 's' in live view to save a png

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Natt #17
metadata.description:
Natt is a short exploration of a view. On not so recent travels I captured a photo of a small town across a large body of water. It was night and the photograph was blurry, but the emotion stayed with me. It was an emotion of calm and tranquility, accepting the darkness of night and knowing that across the water was a group of people living together, creating a beacon of light. 

Natt is the generative take on this photograph, attempting to capture the same emotion in a purely digital format. 


Press â€œspaceâ€ to pause the animation and â€œsâ€ to save the current view.

For higher resolutions, add â€œ?pd=xâ€ (x being a number >1) to the url when in live view and refresh, then press â€œsâ€ to save. Note, for higher values of â€œxâ€ rendering will take longer, start with a low number like 2-3 and work your way up to the desired size.

metadata.name: sewn gate #4
metadata.description:
Now what?
Warmth and comfort?

The lines create carpet patterns with different patterns and angles each time. Squares, rhombuses, plain embroidery and many others.
Why carpets?

They are very attractive with their comfort. A house or apartment with carpets always seems more residential and warm, no matter what kind of carpet. One color or pattern doesn't matter. It performs not only a design or warming function, but also a pleasant one for the soul. I hope I was able to make your day comfortable!

metadata.name: Thalassophobia #42
metadata.description:
Thalassophobia is defined as the terror of deep water. The composition features a winding and cyclical path made from colored circles and light texture, which represents how fear consumes and grows.

Circles and paths were chosen to form a visually simple system, and in part because these elements are deeply important symbols.

The start point for the looping path is randomized for each output. Transparency variations soften the transition where the cycle begins and ends, with the last circle almost completely transparent drawn over the first.

Color gradients were created that smoothly transition and completely cycle, with different start points on each run. The light texturing of lines, varied transparency and partial occlusion cues together create a subtle impression of depth and structure.

Each output from this algorithm features a circuitous path established around 2-6 randomized switchbacks, with small, medium or large circles. Those two characteristics affect the rarity of the output, while the color gradients have equal likelihood among 15 options.

This system was originally composed in R code, then translated to p5.js for fxhash.

Verified NFT collectors can purchase a fine art print for their unique token at vadenart.com


About the artist: Kenny Vaden is a generative artist based in Charleston, SC. His art experience included drawing, painting, stained glass apprenticeships, and nature photography. Vadenâ€™s code-based artworks are available online as limited edition or single edition fine art prints, as well as NFTs on Quantum.art, Flamingo DAO Flutter, OpenSea, Objkt, and Foundation. metadata.name: September #211
metadata.description:
The Summer Ends
---------------
Controls:
S or double tap (mobile): Download image

A: Toggle loading animation (off by default to improve performance)

1-6: Modify scale (1 = default, 1500 x 2000px, 6 = maximum, 9000 x 12000px (performance intensive, will take a long time to render))
F: Fit to current screen size

T: Toggle grain and texture overlay
H: Toggle shape outlines

B: Cycle border sizes (0 -> 50 -> 75 -> 100 -> 150px)
C: Cycle border colors

I: Cycle visible layers

L: Toggle â€œlive modeâ€. This mode will continuously redraw a new output every few seconds using the same base parameters as the original output, but with slight variations.

You can modify the x and y url parameters to set a custom size. Note that the image will change to fit the new size, but overall drawing style, colors, etc. will remain the same.
(For example, for a 1000x2000 image, add &x=1000&y=2000)
